{"title_page": "In the Mountain in the Cloud", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = In the Mountain in the Cloud\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Portugal. The Man]]\n| cover      = In the Mountain in the Cloud.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2011|7|19}}\n| recorded   = Summer 2010 \u2013 March 2011\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{flatlist|\n*LA Bronz\n*[[Kingsize Soundlabs]]\n*White House Recorders\n*Rusty Branson's Pleasure Cave\n*[[Sonic Ranch]] Studios}}\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Psychedelic rock]]\n*[[progressive rock]]\n*[[glam rock]]\n*[[art rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 44:00\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer   = [[John Hill (producer)|John Hill]], John Gourley, [[Casey Bates]]\n| prev_title = [[American Ghetto]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[Evil Friends]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = In the Mountain in the Cloud\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\n | single1date = May 17, 2011<ref name=\"Got It All\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/got-it-all-this-cant-be-living/id435395973  |title=Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now) - Single by Portugal. The Man |publisher=[[iTunes]] (US) |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>\n | single2     = So American\n | single2date = October 7, 2011<ref name=\"So American\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/pl/album/so-american-single/id469942961 |title=So American - Single by Portugal. The Man |publisher=[[iTunes]] (PL) |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''In the Mountain in the Cloud''''' is the sixth studio album by Alaskan [[psychedelic rock]] band [[Portugal. The Man]]. It was recorded over a period of eight months, and produced by [[John Hill (producer)|John Hill]], the band's frontman John Gourley, and [[Casey Bates]]. The album was released on July 19, 2011 through [[Atlantic Records]] and is Portugal. The Man's major-label debut.\n\nThe album was promoted by the singles \"Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\" and \"So American\". It received favorable reviews from music critics, and charted in the US, Austria, Germany and Switzerland.\n\n==Background and recording==\n''In the Mountain in the Cloud'' is Portugal. The Man's major-label debut, as the band was signed to [[Atlantic Records]] in April 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/portugal._the_man_sign_to_atlantic |title=Portugal. The Man sign to Atlantic |work=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]] |date=April 2, 2010 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Oregon Live\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/music/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_portugal_the_man_rel.html |title=Portland's Portugal. The Man releases major label debut, 'In The Mountain In The Cloud' |first=Ryan |last=White |publisher=Oregon Live |date=July 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref> shortly after the release of its fifth studio album ''[[American Ghetto]]'', the creation of which took only 10 days.<ref name=\"Paste background\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/av/2011/07/album-stream-portugal-the-man---in-the-mountain-in.html |title=Album Stream: Portugal. The Man - In The Mountain In The Cloud |first=Andrea |last=Kszystyniak |work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date=July 13, 2011 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPortugal. The Man started the relationship with the label by lying that the songs for the sixth studio album were ready. As the band had a more \"generous\" timeline than in the past, they went to [[Seattle]] to work on some songs, and came out with only one. Then they joined producer [[John Hill (record producer)|John Hill]] in a studio in [[El Paso]], where they managed to write one song, \"Floating (Time Isn't Working My Side)\". The band members noticed that for the first time they weren't able to communicate,<ref name=\"Oregon Live\"/><ref name=\"Paste background\"/> and decided they needed some space to regroup.<ref name=\"Paste background\"/> Hill and singer/songwriter John Gourley went to [[New York City|New York]], while other members of the band returned to [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]. Gourley would call them to say what he needed, and they would record and e-mail, however, the distance complicated communication even further. In a midway of the creative process, Gourley said to Hill during an argument that he was going to quit the band and \"go back to Alaska and build houses.\"<ref name=\"Oregon Live\"/>\n\nIn an interview with MTV News, Gourley said that the band \"wrote the album, did pre-production and then everything fell apart.\" The band would go into the studio, \"mess everything up,\" leave the studio to go on tour, and then try again.<ref name=\"MTV background\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1667498/portugal-the-man-new-album-mountain-cloud/ |title=Portugal. The Man Make The Leap On New Album |first=James |last=Montgomery |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=July 19, 2011 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref> \"All Your Light (Times Like These)\" was written in [[San Diego]], \"Head Is a Flame (Cool With It)\" \u2013 in [[Los Angeles]], and \"Sleep Forever\" was written in Seattle, where the band worked with an old friend, producer [[Casey Bates]]. After several months of struggle the record started to take shape. The recording of ''In the Mountain in the Cloud'' was wrapped in March 2011, after eight months.<ref name=\"Oregon Live\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThe release of the album was announced on April 29, 2011, with an official release date of July 19, 2011.\n\nOn May 17, 2011, four versions of pre-order packs were made available, all with an immediate download of the song \"Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\". \"Just the Music\" pack consisted of a deluxe edition CD, a vinyl or digital download. In addition to the CD, white vinyl or digital download, \"Deluxe Pack\" also had a T-shirt, while \"Premium Pack\" included a T-shirt, a set of three Field Journals and two patches. A \"Limited Edition Pack\", consisting of a specially packaged CD and white vinyl, digital download, T-shirt, lithograph and the set of three Field Journals and two patches, was also released in a number of 500 copies.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\n==Promotion and short film==\n{{Section OR|date=May 2014}}\nStarting April 7, 2011, Portugal. The Man started posting new music via their YouTube account.\n*\"Once Was One\" (April 7, 2011) - 30-Second Preview\n*\"All Your Light\" (April 14, 2011) - 30-Second Preview\n*\"So American\" (April 21, 2011) - 30-Second Preview\n*\"You Carried Us (Share With Me The Sun)\" (April 26, 2011) - 30-Second Preview\n*\"Got it All (This Can't Be Living Now)\" (April 29, 2011) - Full Stream\n*\"Sleep Forever\" (May 5, 2011) - Full Stream\n\nOn May 27, 2011, Portugal. The Man posted these samples for streaming via [[SoundCloud]].\n\nOn June 6, 2011, Portugal. The Man released a short film entitled \"Sleep Forever\" via [[Independent Film Channel|IFC]]. The film acted as an extended music video for the songs \"Sleep Forever\" and \"Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\". The film depicted frontman John Baldwin Gourley on a dog-sled, riding through the Alaskan wilderness. At one point, the dogs go missing and John runs off to look for them. He trips in the snow and his gun discharges and kills him. While lying in the snow, one of his missing dogs starts to eat John while he sings \"Got It All\". During that song, the scene switches from the dog eating John and him singing in an igloo behind a fire. Then, the camera sets on a mountain side with three strange lights and ends. A bit of the footage was originally shown in the 30-second previews for \"Once Was One\", \"All Your Light (Times Like These)\", \"So American\" and \"You Carried Us (Share With Me The Sun)\".\n\nAt one point, before the album was released, you could purchase Portugal. The Man [[iPhone]] cases.\n\nThe artwork for the Deluxe edition of the album is a fold-out layout, the same as their 2009 album ''[[The Satanic Satanist]]''.\n\n\"All Your Light\" is featured in a 2015 Gatorade commercial featuring NBA player [[Jabari Parker]]. The song is also featured in [[Red Bull]]'s 2015 BMX video ''Kaleidoscope'' featuring Red Bull sponsored athlete Kriss Kyle.<ref>http://kaleidoscope.redbull.com/?wtk=YTRef</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 73/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for In the Mountain in the Cloud |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud-r2210426 |title=In the Mountain in the Cloud - Portugal. The Man |first=Gregory |last=Heaney |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n| rev3 = Blare\n| rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Blare\">{{cite web|url=http://blaremagazine.com/2011/08/16/review-portugal-the-man-in-the-mountain |title=REVIEW: Portugal. The Man \u2013 \"In The Mountain, In The Cloud\" |first=Joshua |last=Khan |publisher=Blare |date=August 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Consequence of Sound]]\n| rev4Score = C+<ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/07/album-review-portugal-the-man-in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud/ |title=Album Review: Portugal. The Man \u2014 In the Mountain, In the Cloud |first=Alex |last=Young |publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=July 18, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev5 = Cinema Blend\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/pop/Review-Portugal-Man-Mountain-Cloud-33629.html |title=Review: Portugal. The Man In The Mountain In The Cloud |publisher=Cinema Blend |first=Joseph |last=Giannone |date=July 20, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n| rev7 = [[Paste Magazine]]\n| rev7Score = (8.3/10)<ref name=\"Paste\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2011/07/portugal-the-man-in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud.html |title=Portugal. The Man: In the Mountain, In the Cloud |publisher=[[Paste Magazine]] |first=Wyndham |last=Wyeth |date=July 19, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|6|10}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/reviews/portugal-man-mountain-cloud-atlantic |title=Portugal. The Man., 'In the Mountain in the Cloud' (Atlantic) |work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]] |first=David |last=Marchese |date=July 19, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev9Score ={{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud-20110816 |title=In the Mountain in the Cloud |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |first=J. Edward |last=Keyes |date=August 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n|rev10=Under the Gun Review\n|rev10score=9/10 <ref name=\"Under The Gun Review\">{{cite web |url=http://www.underthegunreview.net/2011/07/24/review-portugal-the-man-in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud/ |title=REVIEW: Portugal. The Man: 'In The Mountain, In The Cloud' |publisher=Under the Gun Review |date=July 24, 2011 |access-date=November 22, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202232059/http://www.underthegunreview.net/2011/07/24/review-portugal-the-man-in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud/ |archive-date=December 2, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n}}\nThe album has gathered generally favorable reviews from music critics. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an average score of 73, based on 13 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{track listing\n| all_writing     = [[John Gourley|John Baldwin Gourley]]\n| title1          = So American\n| length1         = 3:36\n| title2          = Floating (Time Isn't Working My Side)\n| length2         = 3:36\n| title3          = Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\n| length3         = 3:46\n| title4          = Senseless\n| length4         = 3:26\n| title5          = Head Is a Flame (Cool with It)\n| length5         = 3:33\n| title6          = You Carried Us (Share with Me the Sun)\n| length6         = 4:07\n| title7          = Everything You See (Kids Count Hallelujahs)\n| length7         = 4:15\n| title8          = All Your Light (Times Like These)\n| length8         = 4:26\n| title9          = Once Was One\n| length9         = 4:22\n| title10         = Share with Me the Sun\n| length10        = 2:44\n| title11         = Sleep Forever\n| length11        = 6:19\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Portugal. The Man<ref name=\"credits\">Credits adapted from deluxe edition CD liner notes</ref>\n*John Baldwin Gourley \u2013 vocals, guitar, synth\n*Zachary Scott Carothers \u2013 bass, percussion, vocals\n*Ryan Neighbors \u2013 piano, Rhodes, organ, synth, Farfisa, vocals\n*Jason Sechrist \u2013 drums, vocals\n\n;Additional musicians<ref name=\"credits\"/>\n*Philip Peterson \u2013 strings, horns, Arranging \n*[[Steven Nistor]] \u2013 additional drums\n*Sonny DiPerri \u2013 additional drums\n\nRecorded at LA Bronz {{small|([[Los Angeles]])}}, [[Kingsize Soundlabs]] {{small|(Los Angeles)}}, White House Recorders {{small|([[San Diego]], CA)}}, Rusty Branson's Pleasure Cave {{small|([[New York City]])}}, [[Sonic Ranch]] Studios {{small|([[Texas]])}}.\n\nMastered at [[Sterling Sound]] {{small|(New York City)}}.\n\n{{col-2}}\n;Technical personnel<ref name=\"credits\"/>\n*[[John Hill (record producer)|John Hill]] \u2013 production\n*John Gourley \u2013 co-production, design, photography\n*[[Casey Bates]] \u2013 co-production, engineering\n*[[Andy Wallace (producer)|Andy Wallace]] \u2013 mixing\n*Paul Suarez \u2013 digital editing\n*John Morrical \u2013 engineering, editing\n*Michael Freyer \u2013 engineering\n*Alex Leader \u2013 engineering\n*Shaun Cornell \u2013 engineering\n*Ben Hasdovic \u2013 engineering\n*Sonny DiPerri \u2013 engineering, engineering assistant\n*[[Manuel Calderon (musician)|Manuel Calderon]] \u2013 engineering assistant\n*Greg Calbi \u2013 mastering\n*Austin Sellers \u2013 design\n*Zach Carothers \u2013 photography\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"|Chart (2011)\n! scope=\"col\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Austria|60|artist=Portugal. The Man|album=In the Mountain in the Cloud|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Germany3|97|artist=Portugal. The Man|album=In the Mountain in the Cloud|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Switzerland|70|artist=Portugal. The Man|album=In the Mountain in the Cloud|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|42|artist=Portugal. The Man|artistid=347085|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardAlternative|11|artist=Portugal. The Man|artistid=347085|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|BillboardRock|12|artist=Portugal. The Man|artistid=347085|rowheader=true|accessdate=May 20, 2014}}\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Portugal. The Man}}\n\n[[Category:2011 albums]]\n[[Category:Atlantic Records albums]]\n[[Category:Portugal. The Man albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by John Hill (record producer)]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Sonic Ranch]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Kingsize Soundlabs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = In the Mountain in the Cloud\n| type       = Studio\n| artist     = [[Portugal. The Man]]\n| cover      = In the Mountain in the Cloud.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|2011|7|19}}\n| recorded   = Summer 2010 \u2013 March 2011\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{flatlist|\n*LA Bronz\n*[[Kingsize Soundlabs]]\n*White House Recorders\n*Rusty Branson's Pleasure Cave\n*[[Sonic Ranch]] Studios}}\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n*[[Psychedelic rock]]\n*[[progressive rock]]\n*[[glam rock]]\n*[[art rock]]\n}}\n| length     = 44:00\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| producer   = [[John Hill (producer)|John Hill]], John Gourley, [[Casey Bates]]\n| prev_title = [[American Ghetto]]\n| prev_year  = 2010\n| next_title = [[Evil Friends]]\n| next_year  = 2013\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = In the Mountain in the Cloud\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\n | single1date = May 17, 2011<ref name=\"Got It All\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/got-it-all-this-cant-be-living/id435395973  |title=Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now) - Single by Portugal. The Man |publisher=[[iTunes]] (US) |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>\n | single2     = So American\n | single2date = October 7, 2011<ref name=\"So American\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/pl/album/so-american-single/id469942961 |title=So American - Single by Portugal. The Man |publisher=[[iTunes]] (PL) |accessdate=May 21, 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''In the Mountain in the Cloud''''' is the sixth studio album by Alaskan [[psychedelic rock]] band [[Portugal. The Man]]. It was recorded over a period of eight months, and produced by [[John Hill (producer)|John Hill]], the band's frontman John Gourley, and [[Casey Bates]]. The album was released on July 19, 2011 through [[Atlantic Records]] and is Portugal. The Man's major-label debut.\n\nThe album was promoted by the singles \"Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\" and \"So American\". It received favorable reviews from music critics, and charted in the US, Austria, Germany and Switzerland.\n\n==Background and recording==\n''In the Mountain in the Cloud'' is Portugal. The Man's major-label debut, as the band was signed to [[Atlantic Records]] in April 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.altpress.com/news/entry/portugal._the_man_sign_to_atlantic |title=Portugal. The Man sign to Atlantic |work=[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]] |date=April 2, 2010 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Oregon Live\">{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/music/index.ssf/2011/07/portlands_portugal_the_man_rel.html |title=Portland's Portugal. The Man releases major label debut, 'In The Mountain In The Cloud' |first=Ryan |last=White |publisher=Oregon Live |date=July 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref> shortly after the release of its fifth studio album ''[[American Ghetto]]'', the creation of which took only 10 days.<ref name=\"Paste background\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/blogs/av/2011/07/album-stream-portugal-the-man---in-the-mountain-in.html |title=Album Stream: Portugal. The Man - In The Mountain In The Cloud |first=Andrea |last=Kszystyniak |work=[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]] |date=July 13, 2011 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPortugal. The Man started the relationship with the label by lying that the songs for the sixth studio album were ready. As the band had a more \"generous\" timeline than in the past, they went to [[Seattle]] to work on some songs, and came out with only one. Then they joined producer [[John Hill (record producer)|John Hill]] in a studio in [[El Paso]], where they managed to write one song, \"Floating (Time Isn't Working My Side)\". The band members noticed that for the first time they weren't able to communicate,<ref name=\"Oregon Live\"/><ref name=\"Paste background\"/> and decided they needed some space to regroup.<ref name=\"Paste background\"/> Hill and singer/songwriter John Gourley went to [[New York City|New York]], while other members of the band returned to [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]]. Gourley would call them to say what he needed, and they would record and e-mail, however, the distance complicated communication even further. In a midway of the creative process, Gourley said to Hill during an argument that he was going to quit the band and \"go back to Alaska and build houses.\"<ref name=\"Oregon Live\"/>\n\nIn an interview with MTV News, Gourley said that the band \"wrote the album, did pre-production and then everything fell apart.\" The band would go into the studio, \"mess everything up,\" leave the studio to go on tour, and then try again.<ref name=\"MTV background\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1667498/portugal-the-man-new-album-mountain-cloud/ |title=Portugal. The Man Make The Leap On New Album |first=James |last=Montgomery |publisher=[[MTV]] |date=July 19, 2011 |accessdate=May 30, 2014}}</ref> \"All Your Light (Times Like These)\" was written in [[San Diego]], \"Head Is a Flame (Cool With It)\" \u2013 in [[Los Angeles]], and \"Sleep Forever\" was written in Seattle, where the band worked with an old friend, producer [[Casey Bates]]. After several months of struggle the record started to take shape. The recording of ''In the Mountain in the Cloud'' was wrapped in March 2011, after eight months.<ref name=\"Oregon Live\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThe release of the album was announced on April 29, 2011, with an official release date of July 19, 2011.\n\nOn May 17, 2011, four versions of pre-order packs were made available, all with an immediate download of the song \"Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\". \"Just the Music\" pack consisted of a deluxe edition CD, a vinyl or digital download. In addition to the CD, white vinyl or digital download, \"Deluxe Pack\" also had a T-shirt, while \"Premium Pack\" included a T-shirt, a set of three Field Journals and two patches. A \"Limited Edition Pack\", consisting of a specially packaged CD and white vinyl, digital download, T-shirt, lithograph and the set of three Field Journals and two patches, was also released in a number of 500 copies.{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\n==Promotion and Short Film==\n{{Section OR|date=May 2014}}\nStarting April 7, 2011, Portugal. The Man started posting new music via their YouTube account.\n*\"Once Was One\" (April 7, 2011) - 30-Second Preview\n*\"All Your Light\" (April 14, 2011) - 30-Second Preview\n*\"So American\" (April 21, 2011) - 30-Second Preview\n*\"You Carried Us (Share With Me The Sun)\" (April 26, 2011) - 30-Second Preview\n*\"Got it All (This Can't Be Living Now)\" (April 29, 2011) - Full Stream\n*\"Sleep Forever\" (May 5, 2011) - Full Stream\n\nOn May 27, 2011, Portugal. The Man posted these samples for streaming via [[SoundCloud]].\n\nOn June 6, 2011, Portugal. The Man released a short film entitled \"Sleep Forever\" via [[Independent Film Channel|IFC]]. The film acted as an extended music video for the songs \"Sleep Forever\" and \"Got It All (This Can't Be Living Now)\". The film depicted frontman John Baldwin Gourley on a dog-sled, riding through the Alaskan wilderness. At one point, the dogs go missing and John runs off to look for them. He trips in the snow and his gun discharges and kills him. While lying in the snow, one of his missing dogs starts to eat John while he sings \"Got It All\". During that song, the scene switches from the dog eating John and him singing in an igloo behind a fire. Then, the camera sets on a mountain side with three strange lights and ends. A bit of the footage was originally shown in the 30-second previews for \"Once Was One\", \"All Your Light (Times Like These)\", \"So American\" and \"You Carried Us (Share With Me The Sun)\".\n\nAt one point, before the album was released, you could purchase Portugal. The Man [[iPhone]] cases.\n\nThe artwork for the Deluxe edition of the album is a fold-out layout, the same as their 2009 album ''[[The Satanic Satanist]]''.\n\n\"All Your Light\" is featured in a 2015 Gatorade commercial featuring NBA player [[Jabari Parker]]. The song is also featured in [[Red Bull]]'s 2015 BMX video ''Kaleidoscope'' featuring Red Bull sponsored athlete Kriss Kyle.<ref>http://kaleidoscope.redbull.com/?wtk=YTRef</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 73/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud/critic-reviews |title=Critic Reviews for In the Mountain in the Cloud |publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allmusic.com/album/in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud-r2210426 |title=In the Mountain in the Cloud - Portugal. The Man |first=Gregory |last=Heaney |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]''\n| rev2score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n| rev3 = Blare\n| rev3score = {{Rating|3.5|5}}<ref name=\"Blare\">{{cite web|url=http://blaremagazine.com/2011/08/16/review-portugal-the-man-in-the-mountain |title=REVIEW: Portugal. The Man \u2013 \"In The Mountain, In The Cloud\" |first=Joshua |last=Khan |publisher=Blare |date=August 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev4 = [[Consequence of Sound]]\n| rev4Score = C+<ref name=\"CoS\">{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/07/album-review-portugal-the-man-in-the-mountain-in-the-cloud/ |title=Album Review: Portugal. The Man \u2014 In the Mountain, In the Cloud |first=Alex |last=Young |publisher=[[Consequence of Sound]] |date=July 18, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev5 = Cinema Blend\n| rev5Score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinemablend.com/pop/Review-Portugal-Man-Mountain-Cloud-33629.html |title=Review: Portugal. The Man In The Mountain In The Cloud |publisher=Cinema Blend |first=Joseph |last=Giannone |date=July 20, 2011 |accessdate=May 20, 2014}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev6Score = {{Rating|7|10}}<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n| rev7 = [[Paste Magazine]]\n| rev7Score = (8.3/10)<ref name=\"Paste\">{{cite web|url=http